messages.message:
Hey team, received some feedback from an interview candidate based on their experience with AI Hub during the tech screen. Some of these points are general product feedback/signal, while others might be bugs.

I've asked them for project and app URLs and will post them here once I get them.

cc @Jasper @Faheem @jean @hannah

Thanks Hamish! This is great.

• For logged out website feedback, tagging in @alagu 
• For converse sample prompts, tagging in @margaret.tomaszczuk 
• For UX navigation, this should be fixed soon with some of the upcoming top nav changes
• For free trial, we can consider adding this to text (agree this is a big selling point). I'll add this to one of our tickets where we are fixing a few things in the sign up flow. 
• On the build and ground truth bugs adding in @Serena 
• For the API feedback and bugs, adding in @Anil

We’re aware of the SDK docs gap,, but that work is now in progress. It’s helpful to hear the expectations around this! I suspect “this page” is an API doc? cc: @Chris Cowell

Thank you for passing this on, @Hamish, and please pass on our thanks to the candidate if you get the chance!

> • when creating classes before uploading documents, the classification returned errors
i can’t reproduce on prod - can we ask this candidate to clarify?

> • there seemed to be some buggy behavior in deleted unwanted table rows
for the specific human review issue with the table header and deleting the first row, i think that might be expected? cc @Udit to confirm

He said he created the classes and added fields and then uploaded the docs which resulted in errors. My feel for this was it was a request overload because all docs would've been added and extractions applied at once.
is this the same candidate mentioned in this thread (https://instabase.slack.com/archives/C05BJCNKZAM/p1734534641693609?thread_ts=1734528744.695529&cid=C05BJCNKZAM)?
ok i’ll follow up in that thread!

@Hamish @jean Bullet #8 in the list is now fixed — thanks for pointing out that code bug. I’ve got it on my to do list to run through every code sample to check for drift, like happened here.

Like Jean said, addressing bullet #7 is a work in progress. Glad to get that input from a user though.
